<br>
However, even if I made a mistake, it was not an unreasonable one.  I applied several rules-of-thumb that have served me well.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1) Beastlord threads are asking for trouble.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
As soon as I saw it, I knew it was likely to be trouble.  There are several topics I keep an eye out on.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>2) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> shows no respect for others.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This I have seen over and over again.  Worse, he makes almost no positive contributions to the community in terms of sharing techniques, observations, data, new ideas, etc.  His posts largely consist of two things: mages suck, and anyone who disagrees with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> sucks.  Thus I have little tolerance for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>3) Content and ideas balance the occasional mistake.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
We are all human and these are emotional subjects.  What are the odds that someone can always avoid inflammatory language.  In the case of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Wezloc</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s post, there was a fair amount of materiel with one slip up mixed in.  Therefore, I did not decide to blame <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Wezloc</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s message was short, and emphasized disrespect.  As usual, he did not merely disagree or attempt to correct another poster's misapprehension, but implied that the poster was an uninformed idiot, even if he did not say so directly.  Since the few sentences <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> wrote emphasized disrespect, I took that as his primary motivation.  This is consistant with his history here and elsewhere.<br>
<br>
I may have overreacted to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s post, but in that call between <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Wezloc</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, I think I was still correct.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Wezloc</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s post was on the whole informative and only incidently insulting, whereas I read <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s post as on the whole insulting, and only incidently informative.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>4) Warn one, warn all.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I find generally that if I take the worst offender in a thread and make an example of them, other people get the message as well.  I already explained why I chose <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
As for favoritism, I have taken <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Wezloc</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to task many times, and warned him strongly in public on more than one occasion.<br>
<br>
Again, it is neither the poster, or their opinions, but the respect they show towards others that matters to me. <br>
